ions wrought and felt by the union, and the character of the union members and leaders. Critical throughout is discussion of the role of Philip Murray in shaping the United Steelworkers of America into one of the premier economic, social, and political institution of the war years and beyond. Contributors: David Brody, Malvyn Dubovsky, Ronald L. Filippelli, Mark McColloch, Ronald W. Schatz  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aIron and steel workersxLabor unionszUnited StatesxHistoryvCongresses. 4aLabor History. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aAbel, I. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrody, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurke, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Paul F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDubofsky, Melvyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFilippelli, Ronald L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGottlieb, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHoerr, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Donald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcColloch, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaskin, Abe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuttenberg, Harold J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchatz, Ronald W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org